going?\n\nThis dummy articl...',NULL,'The Homepage Question Every Visitor Is Asking','Visitors may not say it out loud, but they are always asking the same thing: is this for me, and should I trust it enough to keep going?\n\nThis dummy articl...','/images/blog/101926115-2croppedemoji.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 04:36:57','2026-03-25 04:36:57',7),(24,'Timing the Market: A Case Study in What Actually Pays Off','timing-the-market-case-study','Timing the market is less about predicting the perfect moment and more about being ready when the right opportunity appears. This case-study-style article explains why.','<p>Timing the market sounds powerful because it suggests there is a perfect moment hiding somewhere ahead, just waiting to be found. In the current housing market, that idea is tempting. Freddie Mac reported the average 30-year fixed mortgage rate at 6.22% on March 19, 2026, and the National Association of REALTORS® reported February existing-home sales running at a 4.09 million annual pace with 1.29 million homes on the market, equal to 3.8 months of supply. In other words, conditions are active enough to create opportunity, but expensive enough to punish hesitation that has no plan behind it.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>A useful way to understand timing the market is through a simple case study.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Consider three buyers watching the same market.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The first buyer decides to wait for rates to fall sharply before doing anything. The logic sounds smart: why buy at today’s rate if tomorrow’s might be lower? The problem is that this buyer treats timing as prediction instead of preparation. Realtor.com’s 2026 forecast expects mortgage rates to average about 6.3% this year, with existing-home sales rising modestly and inventory improving nearly 9% year over year. That suggests some relief, but not a dramatic reset. So the first buyer may wait for a huge break that never fully arrives, while better-prepared buyers step into improving inventory before competition strengthens again.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The second buyer waits for home prices to fall hard. This buyer believes patience alone will create a bargain. But the current market is not behaving like a simple crash story. NAR’s latest snapshot still showed a February median existing-home price of $398,000, up 0.3% from a year earlier. Inventory has improved, but supply remains limited enough that well-priced homes can still attract serious attention. In this case, the buyer may be directionally right that some sellers are more negotiable than before, but wrong to assume that every delay automatically produces a cheaper outcome.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The third buyer takes a different approach. This buyer watches the market, but does not worship it. They improve credit, protect cash reserves, get pre-approved, study neighborhoods, and decide in advance what monthly payment, condition level, and location make sense. When the right home appears, they move. If rates fall later, they may refinance. If inventory continues to improve, they already know how to compare options without panic. Their timing is not based on guessing the exact bottom. It is based on being ready when a workable opportunity appears.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>That is the optimistic lesson. In today’s market, timing still matters, but not in the dramatic way many people imagine. The advantage is shifting away from perfect prediction and toward disciplined readiness. A buyer who is financially organized, emotionally clear, and realistic about trade-offs can benefit in a market like this because modestly improving supply creates choices, while the absence of a full affordability breakthrough keeps weaker competition on the sidelines.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>So the real case study is not about who guessed the future perfectly. It is about who was ready enough to act when the numbers, the property, and the life plan finally aligned. In this market, that buyer still has a real chance to win.</p>','Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market Survey; National Association of REALTORS® Existing-Home Sales Report and Housing Snapshot; Realtor.com 2026 Housing Forecast','/images/blog/pexels-kindelmedia-7578859.jpg',0,'published','2026-03-25 19:16:29','Timing the Market in 2026 | A Case Study for Home Buyers','An optimistic case-study look at what timing the market really means for buyers in today’s housing environment.','https://getawestruk.com/blog/timing-the-market-case-study','Timing the Market: A Case Study in What Actually Pays Off','Waiting for the perfect moment can cost buyers more than they think. This case study explains what timing the market really rewards.','/images/blog/timing-the-market-case-study-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 19:15:58','2026-03-25 19:16:29',9),(25,'Property Taxes: The Questions You Need to Ask Before You Buy','property-taxes-home-buying-questions','Property taxes can quietly wreck affordability in today’s housing market. This urgent framework shows the questions buyers need to ask before they commit.','<p>Property taxes do not usually get treated like the urgent part of home buying, but in this market they need to be. As of March 19, 2026, Freddie Mac reported the average 30-year fixed mortgage rate at 6.22%, and NAR reported February existing-home sales at a 4.09 million annual pace, with a median price of $398,000 and just 3.8 months of inventory. That means affordability is already tight, and a tax mistake can push a “workable” payment into dangerous territory fast.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Use this four-question framework before you call any home affordable.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>First: What are the property taxes right now? Not what you hope they are. Not what the listing makes the payment look like. What is the actual annual tax bill attached to the property today? In a market where the price, rate, and insurance cost already demand precision, you cannot afford to treat taxes like a minor line item. They are part of the real cost of ownership.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Second: How do those taxes hit the monthly payment? The CFPB explains that an escrow account is often used to collect money through your monthly mortgage payment for property-related expenses, including taxes. That means property taxes are not some distant bill you worry about later. In many cases, they are already embedded in the monthly number that determines whether the home actually fits your budget.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Third: If taxes rise, do you still have room? This is the question buyers skip when they are emotionally attached. In today’s market, there is less room for thin budgeting. If you are already stretching at today’s rate and today’s tax level, then even a modest increase can create pressure. Urgency matters here because the wrong house is not just expensive on paper. It can become stressful every single month.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Fourth: Are you comparing homes fairly? Two homes at similar prices can carry very different tax burdens. If you compare only list price, you can talk yourself into the wrong choice. A stronger framework is price, rate, taxes, insurance, and total monthly carrying cost together.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>That is the urgent truth: property taxes are not background noise. They are part of the affordability test. In a market that is still expensive, still competitive, and still unforgiving to sloppy math, the buyer who asks sharper tax questions is not being cautious. That buyer is protecting the deal before the deal starts.</p>','Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market Survey; National Association of REALTORS® Existing-Home Sales Housing Snapshot; Consumer Financial Protection Bureau escrow guidance','/images/blog/pexels-olha-ruskykh-7504832.jpg',0,'published','2026-03-25 19:28:20','Property Taxes and Home Buying | The Questions That Matter','An urgent framework for buyers who need to understand how property taxes affect affordability in today’s housing market.','https://getawestruk.com/blog/property-taxes-home-buying-questions','Property Taxes: The Questions You Need to Ask Before You Buy','Property taxes can change what a home really costs. Here is the urgent framework buyers should use before moving forward.','/images/blog/property-taxes-home-buying-questions-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 19:24:42','2026-03-25 19:28:20',9),(26,'Timing the Market: The Comparisons That Matter Before This Market Moves Without You','timing-the-market-comparisons','Timing the market is not just about waiting for lower rates or better prices. This urgent comparison-driven article breaks down what buyers and sellers must weigh in today’s housing market before the window shifts again.','<p>Timing the market sounds smart until you compare it with what people are actually waiting for. Most buyers and sellers are not really waiting for “the right time.” They are waiting for lower rates, lower prices, less competition, more certainty, or a cleaner personal setup. The problem is that those things do not move together. In March 2026, the average 30-year fixed mortgage rate is 6.22%, down from 6.67% a year ago, affordability has improved from last year, inventory is higher than it was in early 2025, and the market is more balanced than it has been in years. But none of that means the market is standing still and waiting for you to feel comfortable.</p>\n<p>That is the first comparison people need to make: waiting for perfection versus acting in an imperfect but usable market. Zillow says agents are seeing buyers gain negotiating power for the first time in years, and Realtor.com says active listings in February were up 7.9% year over year, even though inventory is still 16.8% below typical 2017 to 2019 levels. In plain English, buyers finally have a bit more room, but the market is not flooded with easy choices. It is softer than the frenzy, not soft enough to forgive sloppy timing.</p>\n<p>Now compare waiting for rates to fall with buying before more demand returns. Freddie Mac says rates remain nearly half a percentage point lower than the same time last year, and NAR says February affordability improved to its highest level since March 2022. That sounds encouraging, but it also means other sidelined buyers are getting the same signal you are. When rates ease even a little, some buyers regain confidence, more of them re-enter, and competition can tighten around the good listings first. So the comparison is not simply “today’s rate versus a future lower rate.” It is “today’s rate with today’s competition versus tomorrow’s rate with tomorrow’s competition.” Those are not the same deal.</p>\n<p>Then there is the classic hope that prices will fall enough to make the wait worth it. That hope needs a reality check. NAR says the median existing-home price in February 2026 was $398,000, up 0.3% from a year earlier, while Zillow’s March forecast projects home values to rise 0.7% annually by year-end. Redfin said on March 24 that U.S. home prices in February barely budged month over month, rising just 0.1% on a seasonally adjusted basis, the slowest growth in seven months. That is not a crash setup. That is a slow-growth, market-by-market, highly uneven environment. Compare that with the cost of staying out: another year of rent, another year without equity, another year of exposure to whatever rates do next. For many people, the math of waiting is weaker than the emotion of waiting.</p>\n<p>The same comparison applies to sellers. Too many owners are waiting for a cleaner peak, as if the best selling environment will announce itself with a trumpet. But seller timing is now a comparison between higher seasonal energy and rising seller competition. Realtor.com’s 2026 best-time-to-sell research says the week of April 12 to 18 offers a “Goldilocks” mix of higher prices, stronger demand, faster pace, and fewer competing sellers than the average week. Homes listed during that week have historically reached prices 1.3% higher than the average week and attracted 16.7% more views per listing, while seller competition is typically 11.9% lower than the average week. That is not a guarantee, but it is a sharp reminder that “later” can mean more competitors crowding the same buyer pool.</p>\n<p>And that leads to another critical comparison: price peak versus competition peak. Realtor.com notes that by late June, prices may be near seasonal highs, but new sellers also surge, reaching nearly 1.4 times the level seen at the start of the year in the historical pattern it studied. In other words, some sellers wait for the top line number and forget to compare it with how much harder it may be to stand out once more listings arrive. A seller who lists earlier in a thinner field may get a better overall outcome than a seller who chases a slightly higher theoretical price into a more crowded late-spring market. Timing the market is not just about top-dollar fantasy. It is about timing your leverage against everyone else’s.</p>\n<p>Buyers have their own version of this mistake. They compare spring with fall too casually. Spring usually means more inventory, but it also means more noise, more urgency, and sometimes more emotional bidding around the best homes. Realtor.com notes that buyer competition tends to ease later in the year and that the best time to buy tends to occur in the fall, historically, because views per listing cool and pressure softens. But compare that with the reality of right now: Redfin says the typical home that went under contract in February spent 66 days on the market, the slowest February pace in a decade, and the typical buyer got 1.8% off list price, the biggest February discount since 2023. That means some of the buyer leverage people are waiting for is already here in parts of the market. Waiting until “better later” only works if later is actually better in your area and for your budget.</p>\n<p>Local comparison matters more than national headlines right now. Redfin reported on March 23 that there were 630,000 more home sellers than buyers nationally in February, the biggest gap on record in its data, and said the strongest buyer’s markets are in the South while the strongest seller’s markets are in the Northeast. Realtor.com’s own seller-timing research says the Northeast and Midwest remain more inventory-starved, while the South and West have healthier supply. That means timing the market in Boston is not the same game as timing it in Tampa, and timing it in Columbus is not the same as timing it in Seattle. A person using national headlines as a substitute for local comparison is not timing the market. They are timing a story.</p>\n<p>There is also a brutal but necessary comparison between market timing and financial timing. Some people are trying to optimize the market before they have optimized themselves. They want to buy once rates improve, but they have not cleaned up debt, strengthened reserves, clarified their monthly ceiling, or secured a strong preapproval. Others want to sell once the market heats up, but they have not prepared the house, handled repairs, or chosen a pricing strategy that matches current conditions. The market can help you only if you are ready to use the window when it opens. NAR reports that first-time buyers made up 34% of February sales, up from 31% a year earlier. That is a useful signal: people are not waiting for a flawless backdrop. Many are entering because their finances, not just the headlines, are finally lining up.</p>\n<p>That is why the urgent comparison is not now versus some imaginary perfect later. It is prepared now versus unprepared later. Zillow projects 4.24 million existing-home sales in 2026, up 4.4% from last year, and says improving affordability is expected to support a modest rebound in transactions, even if sales remain below historical norms. If that rebound develops while rates bounce around and inventory growth slows from its recent pace, then buyers and sellers who delayed without a plan may discover they did not avoid risk. They just traded one kind of uncertainty for another.</p>\n<p>The harsh truth is that timing the market is rarely about finding the perfect month. It is about understanding which comparison matters most for your position. If you are a buyer, compare today’s negotiating room with the possibility of future competition. Compare slow price growth with the ongoing cost of waiting. Compare a slightly lower future rate with the chance that good listings will face more attention when that happens. If you are a seller, compare the lure of later-season prices with the reality of growing listing competition. Compare national “best week” guidance with your local inventory conditions. Compare your desired price with your actual preparedness to launch well.</p>\n<p>This market does not reward lazy optimism or frozen caution. It rewards people who compare the right things in the right order and move before the comparison changes against them. Rates are lower than a year ago, affordability is better, inventory is improved, and leverage has shifted enough that both buyers and sellers have real openings right now. But openings close. That is what markets do. If you are going to time this one, stop asking whether the perfect moment is coming and start asking whether the comparison in front of you is already good enough to act on. In 2026, that question is more urgent than most people realize.</p>','Freddie Mac PMMS; National Association of Realtors; Realtor.com Research; Zillow Research; Redfin Research','/images/blog/timing-the-market-comparisons-cover.jpg',0,'draft',NULL,'Timing the Market in 2026 | Buyer and Seller Comparisons That Matter','Compare rates, prices, competition, and timing risks in today’s housing market with this urgent guide for buyers and sellers trying to make the right move.','https://www.yourdomain.com/blog/timing-the-market-comparisons','Timing the Market: The Comparisons That Matter in 2026','An urgent, comparison-driven look at what buyers and sellers should weigh before waiting for a “better” housing market moment.','/images/blog/timing-the-market-comparisons-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 19:34:11','2026-03-25 19:34:11',13),(27,'Home Pricing Trends: 4 Honest Steps to Price Right in Today’s Market','home-pricing-trends-steps','Home pricing in 2026 requires more than guesswork. These honest steps help sellers read current trends, compare the right homes, and price strategically in a more balanced market.','<p>Home pricing feels tricky right now because the market is sending mixed signals. Mortgage rates are still elevated, with Freddie Mac’s 30-year fixed average at 6.22% on March 19, 2026, but inventory is improving, and Realtor.com says national inventory is up 5.6% year over year while list prices have fallen for eight straight weeks. At the same time, NAR reported the median existing-home sale price at $398,000 in February 2026, up just 0.3% from a year earlier. That is not a crash market, but it is a market that punishes sloppy pricing.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Step 1: Price for today’s buyer, not yesterday’s headlines. A lot of sellers still anchor to the hottest numbers from earlier years or to a neighbor’s lucky sale. That is dangerous in a market where buyers have more options and more leverage. Zillow’s March 2026 forecast expects only modest home-value growth this year, and Redfin says February home prices were up just 0.9% year over year nationally. Honest pricing starts with the market you are in now, not the market you wish had come back.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Step 2: Study your live competition. Your real competition is not every home in town. It is the homes a buyer will compare with yours this week. Realtor.com’s March data says buyers are seeing more bargaining power, longer decision windows, and softer list-price trends. That means you should compare condition, updates, location, and presentation against active listings and recent pendings, not just closed sales from months ago.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Step 3: Treat price per square foot as a clue, not a verdict. It helps, but it cannot fully price layout quality, lot value, upgrades, or functional flaws. Realtor.com reported asking prices per square foot dropping to their lowest point in its data history back to 2017, which tells you buyers are getting pickier about value. Use the metric, but do not hide behind it.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Step 4: Leave room for negotiation without overreaching. The smartest list price is the one that attracts attention, creates confidence, and still gives you options. Overpricing usually does not create leverage now. It creates staleness. In this market, clean pricing is strategy. If you want strong interest, price to compete, not to test the ceiling.</p>','Freddie Mac PMMS; Realtor.com Research; National Association of Realtors; Zillow Research; Redfin Research','/images/blog/pexels-artbovich-7031411.jpg',0,'published','2026-03-25 19:36:41','Home Pricing Trends in 2026 | Honest Seller Pricing Steps','Learn honest, practical steps for pricing a home in today’s market using current trends, buyer behavior, and smart seller strategy.','https://www.yourdomain.com/blog/home-pricing-trends-steps','Home Pricing Trends: 4 Honest Steps for Sellers','A clear, honest guide to pricing your home in today’s market using current trends and smarter seller strategy.','/images/blog/home-pricing-trends-steps-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 19:36:12','2026-03-25 19:36:41',14),(28,'Market Trends Myths That Can Hold Buyers and Sellers Back','market-trends-myths-guide','A practical, inspirational guide to the biggest market-trend myths holding buyers and sellers back in today’s housing market.','<p>Market trends are supposed to help people make smarter real estate decisions, but in the current market they are often misunderstood. That is the problem. As of March 19, 2026, Freddie Mac reported the average 30-year fixed mortgage rate at 6.22%. NAR reported February existing-home sales at a 4.09 million annual pace, with 1.29 million homes on the market, 3.8 months of supply, and a median existing-home price of $398,000. Realtor.com’s 2026 forecast also points to a steadier year, with mortgage rates averaging about 6.3%, inventory rising nearly 9%, and existing-home sales improving only modestly. This is not a wild boom, and it is not a collapse. It is a market that rewards clearer thinking.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>Use this guide to clear out the myths that can quietly slow you down.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The first myth is that one national trend tells you everything. It does not. National data can show the direction of rates, supply, and sales, but real decisions happen at the local level. A market can be improving overall while one neighborhood stays tight, overpriced, or highly competitive. The inspirational takeaway is simple: trends should inform your judgment, not replace it.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The second myth is that improving inventory means urgency is gone. More inventory does help, but it does not mean every good opportunity will sit around waiting. When supply is still under four months nationally, the right home in the right area can still move fast. Inspiration here comes from discipline. You do not need panic. You need readiness.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The third myth is that rates alone control the whole story. Rates matter a lot, but they are not the only trend shaping outcomes. Inventory, pricing behavior, local demand, and buyer preparedness all change what is possible. Waiting for one perfect rate headline can make people miss a workable window created by better selection or softer competition.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The fourth myth is that a confusing market means no opportunity exists. In reality, mixed markets often create the best opportunities for serious people because hesitation spreads faster than preparation. Buyers who understand their numbers and sellers who understand realistic positioning can move with confidence while others drift.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>That is the real lesson of today’s market trends. They are not there to intimidate you. They are there to sharpen you. If you stop chasing myths and start reading the market with patience, context, and courage, trends stop feeling like noise and start becoming an advantage.</p>','Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market Survey; National Association of REALTORS® Existing-Home Sales Report and Housing Snapshot; Realtor.com 2026 Housing Forecast','/images/blog/pexels-anastasia-shuraeva-7279327.jpg',0,'published','2026-03-25 19:37:41','Market Trends Myths Guide | What Buyers and Sellers Should Know','An inspirational guide that breaks down common market-trend myths and explains how buyers and sellers can think more clearly in today’s market.','https://getawestruk.com/blog/market-trends-myths-guide','Market Trends Myths That Can Hold Buyers and Sellers Back','Today’s housing market is complex, but the wrong myths make it harder. This guide shows buyers and sellers how to think more clearly.','/images/blog/market-trends-myths-guide-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 19:37:34','2026-03-25 19:37:41',9),(29,'Mortgage Options That Create Real Opportunity','mortgage-options-opportunities','In today’s housing market, the right mortgage option can create real opportunity for buyers who understand how to match loan structure with long-term goals.','<p>In the current market, mortgage strategy matters as much as home selection. With Freddie Mac’s 30-year fixed-rate mortgage averaging 6.22% and the 15-year fixed averaging 5.54% as of March 19, 2026, buyers are still working in a higher-rate environment than many hoped for. At the same time, housing affordability has improved from its recent lows, and existing-home inventory has risen to 3.8 months nationally, giving serious buyers more room to negotiate than they had during the most aggressive seller-driven years.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>That is where opportunity begins. A conventional fixed-rate mortgage remains the clearest path for buyers who want stability and predictable payments. But this market also rewards people who understand the wider menu. A 15-year fixed loan can reduce total interest costs dramatically for buyers with strong monthly income. FHA financing can open the door for buyers who need a lower down payment. VA loans can be especially powerful for eligible borrowers because they may offer more flexible entry terms. The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau also notes that rate type, term, and loan type should be evaluated together rather than as isolated decisions.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>There is also a more tactical opportunity in adjustable-rate mortgages. For the right borrower, an ARM is not simply a risk product. It can be a calculated short-to-medium-term tool, especially for buyers who expect a move, refinance, or income change before the adjustment period begins. The key is discipline: the payment must still make sense if rates do not fall quickly. An ARM should never be used to force affordability that is not truly there.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The serious takeaway is this: today’s mortgage market is not easy, but it is full of openings for buyers who compare structures instead of chasing headlines. When rates are not perfect, the buyer who wins is often the one who chooses the right mortgage, not just the right property. In a market where the median existing-home price was $398,000 in February 2026, financing decisions can determine whether a purchase feels heavy, manageable, or strategically smart for years to come.</p>','Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market Survey; National Association of REALTORS® Existing-Home Sales Housing Snapshot; Consumer Financial Protection Bureau mortgage guidance.','/images/blog/pexels-kindelmedia-7578859.jpg',0,'published','2026-03-25 19:41:51','Mortgage Options That Create Real Opportunity in Today’s Market','Explore mortgage options through an opportunity-focused lens and learn how buyers can use the right loan structure in today’s housing market.','https://www.yourdomain.com/blog/mortgage-options-opportunities','Mortgage Options That Create Real Opportunity','A serious look at how different mortgage options can create opportunities for buyers in the current housing market.','/images/blog/mortgage-options-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 19:41:06','2026-03-25 19:42:17',15),(30,'Selling a Home in 2026 Means Letting Go of the Old Market Story','selling-a-home-2026-trends','Selling a home today requires a different mindset than it did a few years ago. This narrative explains the seller trends shaping strategy in the current market.','<p>A seller walks into this spring thinking the hard part is already done. The house is decent. The neighborhood is solid. The last few years taught everyone that if you put a sign in the yard, buyers would rush in and prove the price right. But the current market is telling a different story now, and the most successful sellers are the ones listening closely enough to hear it. As of March 19, 2026, Freddie Mac reported the average 30-year fixed mortgage rate at 6.22%, and NAR reported that February existing-home sales ran at a 4.09 million annual pace, with 1.29 million homes on the market, 3.8 months of supply, and a median existing-home price of $398,000. This is not a frozen market, but it is no longer a market that lets sellers lean on momentum alone.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>So the story of selling a home right now begins with a shift in posture. The seller who still imagines instant leverage from the moment a listing goes live may be working from an outdated script. Realtor.com’s March housing-trend reporting showed active inventory up 5.6% year over year, while another March weekly report showed homes spending a median of 68 days on the market, five days longer than a year earlier, with the national median listing price down 2.3% year over year. That does not mean homes are not selling. It means sellers are stepping into a market where buyers have more breathing room, more choices, and more reason to compare before they commit.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>In that environment, the first real trend shaping sellers is realism. The home that comes out priced for attention has a different future than the home that comes out priced for nostalgia. Sellers are still achieving meaningful values, but the path is changing. A house now has to compete not only against yesterday’s comps but against the buyer’s monthly payment reality, the growing number of alternatives, and the overall mood of a market that is becoming more selective. The enlightening part is this: realism is not weakness. Realism is strategy. It is how a seller protects momentum before the listing grows stale.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The second trend is presentation with purpose. In a market where inventory is rising, buyers can afford to notice details more sharply. Condition, photos, staging choices, light repairs, and listing quality all matter more when the buyer is not boxed into the first acceptable option. A seller who understands this stops asking, “Will it sell anyway?” and starts asking, “Why should this be the one buyers choose first?” That is a healthier question, and it reflects the market more honestly. Inventory growth does not kill opportunity for sellers. It just shifts opportunity toward the homes that feel most ready.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>The third trend is timing, but not in the dramatic way people often imagine. There is still a seasonal rhythm to the market. NAR notes that sales activity typically increases from February into March, and Realtor.com identified the week of April 12–18, 2026, as the national window expected to offer sellers stronger profit potential with fewer price cuts and nearly 12% fewer sellers than the average week. That does not mean every seller should blindly rush to that date. It means timing still matters when it supports preparation, pricing, and positioning rather than replacing them.</p><p>\r\n</p><p>By the end of this story, the seller who wins is not the one clinging to the old market story. It is the one who understands the new one. Homes can still sell well. Demand still exists. Spring still brings movement. But the market is asking for more discipline now: better pricing, cleaner presentation, and a sharper understanding of what buyers are feeling under today’s rates. That is not bad news. It is clarifying news. Because once a seller sees the market clearly, the strategy becomes clearer too. You do not need the chaos of 2021 to sell well in 2026. You need accuracy, timing, and the willingness to meet the market where it is instead of where it used to be.</p>','Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market Survey; National Association of REALTORS® Existing-Home Sales Housing Snapshot and Existing-Home Sales Explained; Realtor.com Weekly Housing Trends and Best Week to Sell 2026 analysis','/images/blog/pexels-mizunokozuki-13801684.jpg',0,'published','2026-03-25 20:13:12','Selling a Home in 2026 | Trends Shaping the Current Market','An enlightening narrative on the housing-market trends sellers need to understand before listing a home in 2026.','https://getawestruk.com/blog/selling-a-home-2026-trends','Selling a Home in 2026 Means Letting Go of the Old Market Story','The current market is changing how sellers need to price, present, and time a listing. Here is the trend story behind that shift.','/images/blog/selling-a-home-2026-trends-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 20:13:04','2026-03-25 20:20:09',9),(31,'Credit & Home Buying in 2026: The Strategies That Can Quietly Change Your Entire Outcome','credit-home-buying-strategies-2026','Credit can shape far more than mortgage approval in today’s market. This eye-opening exploration shows buyers how credit strategy affects rates, options, and overall home-buying power.','<p>Credit has always mattered in home buying, but in the current market, it matters in a more eye-opening way than many buyers realize. As of March 19, 2026, Freddie Mac says the average 30-year fixed mortgage rate is 6.22%, down from 6.67% a year earlier. At the same time, NAR reports February existing-home sales at a 4.09 million annual pace, with 1.29 million homes in inventory and a 3.8-month supply. This is not a cheap market, but it is a more workable one than many buyers saw last year. That is exactly why credit strategy matters so much right now: when rates are still elevated, the difference between a stronger credit profile and a weaker one can shape not just approval, but the monthly payment that follows you for years.</p>\n<p>The first strategy is to stop treating credit like a mystery and start treating it like pre-negotiation. The CFPB says checking your own credit does not hurt your scores, and it points buyers to AnnualCreditReport.com for free reports. It also warns that errors on your reports can reduce your scores unnecessarily and affect mortgage qualification and pricing. That means one of the smartest moves a buyer can make before talking seriously to lenders is to see the file first, catch mistakes early, and dispute anything inaccurate. In a market where affordability is still tight, fixing a report issue is not a minor cleanup task. It can be a payment strategy.</p>\n<p>The second strategy is to understand which credit score game you are actually playing. CFPB says most mortgage lenders use FICO scores, look at all three major credit bureaus, and typically use the middle score to help decide the rate they offer. It also notes that higher scores make it easier to qualify for a loan and lower interest rates. That is the eye-opening part. Many buyers focus only on whether they can get approved, but approval is only the floor. The real strategy is improving the middle score that lenders will actually use, because in a 6%-plus rate market, even a modest rate improvement can matter over the life of a loan.</p>\n<p>The third strategy is to target the credit factors that move the needle instead of making random financial changes. CFPB says scores are typically influenced by bill-paying history, current unpaid debt, available credit usage, account age, and new applications for credit. That should immediately change how a serious buyer behaves. Paying on time is non-negotiable. Carrying high revolving balances is not harmless. Opening new accounts right before applying for a mortgage is usually bad timing. And taking on fresh debt because you feel “almost ready” can hurt more than people expect. In home buying, credit is not just about being responsible in general. It is about being disciplined at the exact moment discipline matters most.</p>\n<p>The fourth strategy is to shop mortgages intelligently without being scared of the credit pull. CFPB says that within a 45-day window, multiple mortgage credit checks are generally recorded as a single inquiry for scoring purposes. That means buyers can compare lenders, request official Loan Estimates, and look for better terms without assuming they are wrecking their score by doing so. That is a major strategic advantage in this market. With rates still elevated, blindly taking the first offer is often more expensive than shopping carefully. The point is not to collect endless quotes forever. The point is to compress your lender shopping into a smart, focused window and use that comparison to protect your payment.</p>\n<p>The final strategy is to connect credit work to market timing realistically. CFPB’s 2026 homebuying prep guidance says buyers should check credit, assess finances, and decide what they can truly afford before shopping seriously. That fits the current market perfectly. Inventory has improved, sales are still happening, and conditions are more balanced than they were a year ago, but none of that helps much if your credit profile is unprepared. The buyer who treats credit as a quiet, early strategy often ends up with more options, more confidence, and more negotiating strength later. In 2026, credit is not just part of the mortgage process. It is one of the clearest ways to change your home-buying outcome before you ever make an offer.</p>','Freddie Mac PMMS; Consumer Financial Protection Bureau; National Association of Realtors','/images/blog/credit-home-buying-strategies-2026-cover.jpg',0,'draft',NULL,'Credit & Home Buying in 2026 | Strategies That Shape Your Mortgage','Learn how credit strategy affects mortgage rates, approval strength, and home-buying power in today’s housing market.','https://www.yourdomain.com/blog/credit-home-buying-strategies-2026','Credit & Home Buying in 2026: The Strategies That Change Everything','An eye-opening guide to how credit strategy can improve your mortgage options and strengthen your home-buying position.','/images/blog/credit-home-buying-strategies-2026-og.jpg',0,1,1,'2026-03-25 23:48:34','2026-03-25 23:48:34',16),(32,'Sunday Pasta Bake Template','sunday-pasta-bake-template','Lorem ipsum placeholder recipe content for layout, workflow, and archive testing. This draft is designed to populate the recipe section without using final editorial copy.','<h2>Sunday Pasta Bake Template</h2>\n<p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Sed non risus. Suspendisse lectus tortor, dignissim sit amet, adipiscing nec, ultricies sed, dolor. Cras elementum ultrices diam. Maecenas ligula massa, varius a, semper congue, euismod non, mi.</p>\n<p>Proin porttitor, orci nec nonummy molestie, enim est eleifend mi, non fermentum diam nisl sit amet erat. Duis semper. Duis arcu massa, scelerisque vitae, consequat in, pretium a, enim. Pellentesque congue. Ut in risus volutpat libero pharetra tempor.</p>\n<h3>Recipe Template Notes 1</h3>\n<p>Cras vestibulum bibendum augue. Praesent egestas leo in pede. Praesent blandit odio eu enim. Pellentesque sed dui ut augue blandit sodales. Vestibulum ante ipsum primis in faucibus orci luctus et ultrices posuere cubilia curae; Aliquam nibh.</p>\n<ul>\n    <li>Lorem ipsum placeholder ingredient line one.</li>\n    <li>Lorem ipsum placeholder ingredient line two.</li>\n    <li>Lorem ipsum placeholder ingredient line three.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Sed